### Creating Templates ####

Step 1: Include our app to the projects `django_projects/settings.py`
        - Open `blog/apps.py` and copy classname "BlogConfig". 
        - Add this class name to `django_projects/settings.py` under installed app list
            INSTALLED_APPS = [
                            'django.contrib.admin',
                            ...
                            'blog.apps.BlogConfig',
                        ]

Step 2: Remove the HttpResponse from `blog/views.py`

Step 3: Create a new folder called `template/blog/` in blog/ and create html files
        - home.html > for our homepage
        - about.html > for our about page

Step 4: Add following template code to both html files
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
    <head> 
    </head>
    <body>
        <h1>Blog home!</h1>
    </body>
</html>

Step 5: In `views.py`, replace return HttpResponse with render function which pass the string of home.html template.
    def home(request):
        return render(request, 'blog/home.html')
    def about(request):
        return render(request, 'blog/about.html')
    ** The template name should be the relative path from the project root directory to the template file. **
   
Step 6: Dry run test if above code works.
>> python manage.py runserver
** open localhost and verify both page and view its source code **

Step 7: Add posts as lists of dictionary of static post to `views.py`
        posts = [
            {
                'author': 'ShreyaVP',
                'title': 'Blog Post 1',
                'content':'First post content',
                'Date-posted':'August 13, 2025'
            },
            {
                'author': 'Jimin Park',
                'title': 'Blog Post 2',
                'content':'Second post content',
                'Date-posted':'August 15, 2025'
            }
        ]

Step 8: Add posts to homepage.
    def home(request):
        context = {
            'posts': posts
        }
        return render(request, 'blog/home.html', context)

Step 9: Add the posts to homepage.
        Remove heading and using for loop to body in home.html
        <body>
        {% for post in posts %}
            <h1>{{ post.title }}</h1>
            <p>By {{ post.author }} on {{ post.date }}</p>
            <p>{{ post.content }}</p>
        {% endfor %}
    </body>
** code in html file is encoded within {% %} and call variables using {{}} **

Step 10: Add appropriate titles to both html pages, this will display the title in webpage title.
        <head>
            {% if title %}
                <title>Django Blog - {{title}}</title>
            {% else %}
                <title>Django Blog</title>
            {% endif %}   
        </head>
** Refresh the page and check the title of webpage on tabs **

Step 11: Lets add title to About page from `views.py` in render()
    def about(request):
        return render(request, 'blog/about.html', {'title':'About'})
** Verify the same on webpage localhost/about and view its source code **


## Template Inheritance ##
Step 1: create a base.html a parent template for home and about files.
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
{% if title %}
        <title>Django Blog - {{ title }}</title>
    {% else %}
        <title>Django Blog</title>
    {% endif %}
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        {% block content %}{% endblock %}
    </div>
</body>
</html>

Step 2: Call the base.html file in both home.html and about.html
{% extends "blog/base.html" %}

Step 3: Add content block in both home and about
** for about.html **
{% block content %}
    <h1>About Page</h1>
{% endblock content %}
    
Step 4: Run server and verify if the wep app is working with a base template.

## Add bootstrap and css to web app ## 

Step 1: Add bootstrap to make the site look better.
Here, we copied following code from bootstrap site to head of base.html
    <!-- Required meta tags -->
    <meta charset="utf-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1, shrink-to-fit=no">

    <!-- Bootstrap CSS -->
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="https://maxcdn.bootstrapcdn.com/bootstrap/4.0.0/css/bootstrap.min.css" integrity="sha384-Gn5384xqQ1aoWXA+058RXPxPg6fy4IWvTNh0E263XmFcJlSAwiGgFAW/dAiS6JXm" crossorigin="anonymous">

And body tag of base:
    <!-- Optional JavaScript -->
    <!-- jQuery first, then Popper.js, then Bootstrap JS -->
    <script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-3.2.1.slim.min.js" integrity="sha384-KJ3o2DKtIkvYIK3UENzmM7KCkRr/rE9/Qpg6aAZGJwFDMVNA/GpGFF93hXpG5KkN" crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
    <script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/popper.js/1.12.9/umd/popper.min.js" integrity="sha384-ApNbgh9B+Y1QKtv3Rn7W3mgPxhU9K/ScQsAP7hUibX39j7fakFPskvXusvfa0b4Q" crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
    <script src="https://maxcdn.bootstrapcdn.com/bootstrap/4.0.0/js/bootstrap.min.js" integrity="sha384-JZR6Spejh4U02d8jOt6vLEHfe/JQGiRRSQQxSfFWpi1MquVdAyjUar5+76PVCmYl" crossorigin="anonymous"></script>


Step 2: Create folder static/blog in blog folder and added new file `main.css`.
content of that file was download from corey's github repo

Step 3: We have also added few more tags for navigation and toggle pages whose html code was provided by corey
https://github.com/CoreyMSchafer/code_snippets/blob/master/Django_Blog/03-Templates/django_project/blog/templates/blog/base.html

Step 4: Verify the web app work and the design of the web app.







